==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scarce
<hw>Scarce</hw> <pr>(sk⟦acir⟧rs)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Scarcer</adjf>
<pr>(sk⟦acir⟧r"s⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Scarcest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>scars</ets>, OF.
<ets>escars</ets>, <ets>eschars</ets>, LL. <ets>scarpsus</ets>,
<ets>excarpsus</ets>, for L. <ets>excerptus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>excerpere</ets> to pick out, and hence to contract, to shorten;
<ets>ex</ets> (see <er>Ex-</er>) + <ets>carpere</ets>. See
<er>Carpet</er>, and cf. <er>Excerp</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not
plentiful or abundant; in small quantity in proportion to the demand;
not easily to be procured; rare; uncommon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You tell him silver is <qex>scarcer</qex> now in England, and
therefore risen one fifth in value.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scarcest</qex> of all is a Pescennius Niger on a
medallion well preserved.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Scantily supplied (with); deficient (in); -- with
<xex>of</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A region
<xex>scarce</xex> of prey.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sparing; frugal; parsimonious; stingy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Too <xex>scarce</xex> ne too sparing.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make one's self scarce</b></col>, <cd>to decamp; to
depart.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Rare; infrequent; deficient. See
<er>Rare</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scarcely</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Scarce</ent>⟦br⟧
